{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17584229","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17584229"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:42:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:42:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14434"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14434","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14434"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.04,0.89,0.02,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7129"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"60124"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7129","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7129"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14434"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45544"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"40"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4903"},{"type":"tags","id":"4905"},{"type":"tags","id":"4909"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"8423"},{"type":"tags","id":"9857"},{"type":"tags","id":"10214"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17032"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17143"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"60124","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/60124"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following ions is released by the sarcoplasmic reticulum during excitation-contraction coupling in cardiac muscle cells?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Potassium ions","Sodium ions","Calcium ions","Magnesium ions","Chloride ions"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring excitation-contraction coupling in cardiac muscle cells, \u003Cstrong\u003Ecalcium ions\u003C/strong\u003E are released from the sarcoplasmic reticulum. This process is triggered by the action potential that spreads along the T-tubules, causing voltage-gated calcium channels to open. The initial influx of calcium ions stimulates the release of more calcium from the sarcoplasmic reticulum through ryanodine receptors, a process known as calcium-induced calcium release (CICR).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPotassium ions\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Esodium ions\u003C/strong\u003E are important for generating and propagating action potentials but are not released from the sarcoplasmic reticulum during this process. \u003Cstrong\u003EMagnesium ions\u003C/strong\u003E play a role in various cellular processes but are not specifically released during excitation-contraction coupling. \u003Cstrong\u003EChloride ions\u003C/strong\u003E are not directly involved in this process.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe released calcium ions bind to troponin C, initiating the sliding filament mechanism and thereafter result in muscle contractions. ATP is required for muscle relaxation and the active transport of calcium back into the sarcoplasmic reticulum, but it is not released during the excitation-contraction coupling process.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Calcium ions are released from the sarcoplasmic reticulum during excitation-contraction coupling in cardiac muscle cells.","The T-tubule system and sarcoplasmic reticulum play crucial roles in the process of excitation-contraction coupling."],"references":["Nusier M, Shah AK, Dhalla NS. Structure-function relationships and modifications of cardiac sarcoplasmic reticulum Ca2+-transport. Physiol Res. 2021 Dec 30;70(Suppl4):S443-S470. doi: 10.33549/physiolres.934805. PMID: 35199536; PMCID: PMC9054189.","Tortora, G. J., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Cooke, J., Di Pietro, F., Diversi, T., ... \u0026 Summers, S.. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 3rd Asia-Pacific Edition. 2022. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Marks AR. Calcium and the heart: a question of life and death. J Clin Invest. 2003 Mar;111(5):597-600. doi: 10.1172/JCI18067. PMID: 12618512; PMCID: PMC151912."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45544"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14434"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45544","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/45544"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-10T10:03:40+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-10T10:04:35+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7129"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"60124"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"40","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/40"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\u2699\ufe0f","name":"Physiology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"4"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"